Part 1 - Classification

Choosing the response variable

The response variable we have chosen is the logarithmic value of highest yearly income(highest_yearly_earnings_log). It indicates each Youtube channel’s highest estimated yearly income. To reduce the errors of data, I use logarithmic value. As I have already calculate this variable in Project 1, so in this project, we just need to transform it into binary data(hyel_binary). Firstly, I will find the median of ‘hyil_binary’. Secondly, I will assign the variables 0/1 , 0 for the values that lower than median and 1 for these higher than median.

#discard some outliers(cite1:Chatgpt 3.5)
library(dplyr)
z_threshold <- 3
Youtubesta4 <- Youtubesta3 %>%
  mutate(z_score = (highest_yearly_earnings_log - mean(highest_yearly_earnings_log)) / sd(highest_yearly_earnings_log))
Youtubesta5 <- Youtubesta4 %>%
  filter(abs(z_score) <= z_threshold) %>%
  select(-z_score)

#calculate the median
hyel_median <- median(Youtubesta5$highest_yearly_earnings_log)

#create a new binary data based on the comparison to the median
Youtubesta5$hyel_binary <- ifelse(Youtubesta5$highest_yearly_earnings_log > hyel_median, 1, 0)
table(Youtubesta5$hyel_binary)
## 
##   0   1 
## 340 332

Looking at the proportions of outcome target variables selected, we can see that there is an equal split.

Selecting the features

In this part, we will create a “candidate columns” to store some “candidate variables” that we think might affect the target variable, and then we will use some feature selection techniques to select the most relevant features from the candidate variables.Firstly, we will use Fisher’s score.

#Fisher's score(cite2:chatgpt 3.5)
library(caret)
candidate_columns <- c("subscribers","video.views","uploads","subscribers_for_last_30_days","Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment....","Population","Unemployment.rate","Urban_population","highest_monthly_earnings_fix1","videoviews_monthlygrowthrate","videoviews_uploads","earnings_views","created_year","X2022")
Youtubesta5 <- na.omit(Youtubesta5) #omit NA values to make sure the calculation can be executed
Youtubesta5$uploads <- as.numeric(Youtubesta5$uploads) #convert some values into numerical values
Youtubesta5$video.views <- as.numeric(Youtubesta5$video.views) #make sure it's numeric value
Youtubesta5$subscribers_for_last_30_days <- as.numeric(Youtubesta5$subscribers_for_last_30_days)
candidate_features <- Youtubesta5[, candidate_columns]
candidate_features_nona <- na.omit(candidate_features)
custom_fisher_column <- function(x, y) { #define a function to calculate fisher score
  abs(tapply(x, y, mean) - mean(x)) / (tapply(x, y, var) + var(x))
}
fisher_scores_list <- lapply(candidate_features_nona, custom_fisher_column, y = Youtubesta5$hyel_binary)
fisher_scores_df <- data.frame(Feature = colnames(candidate_features_nona), Fisher_Score = unlist(fisher_scores_list))
ranked_features1 <- fisher_scores_df[order(fisher_scores_df$Fisher_Score, decreasing = TRUE), ] #order features in descending order 
selected_features1 <- ranked_features1$Feature[1:4] #select the 4 features with highest fisher score

After the fisher’s score selection, we get the first combination of features which is shown below.

selected_features1

## [2] "videoviews_monthlygrowthrate"           
## [3] "Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment...."
## [4] "Population"

Secondly, we will use information gain to select features.

library(FSelectorRcpp) #(cite3:How is information gain calculated? by Andrew Treadway, https://www.r-bloggers.com/2020/02/how-is-information-gain-calculated/)
information_gains <- information_gain(candidate_features_nona,Youtubesta5$hyel_binary)
ranked_features2 <- information_gains[order(information_gains$importance,decreasing = TRUE), ]
selected_features2 <- ranked_features2$attributes[1:6]

After the information gain selection, we get the second combination of features which is shown below.

# Create a function to plot feature distributions as density plots(cite4: chatgpt 3.5)
nb_density_plot <- function(data, feature_name, train_pred) {
  ggplot(data, aes(x = data[[feature_name]], fill = cut(train_pred, breaks = 5))) +
    geom_density(aes(y = ..count..), alpha = 0.5) +
    labs(title = paste("Density Plot1 of", feature_name), x = feature_name)+project2_theme
}

Comparison of the combinations of feature selection techniques and classifiers

Firstly, the feature selection techniques. From the Naive Bayes model’s results, all the features selected by Information gain show a positive correlation with the response variable, while there are two variables(gross tertiary education enrollment and population) which are selected by Fisher score don’t show a positive correlation with the response variable. So we can draw a conclusion that based on this project, Information gain might be more accurate.

Secondly, the classifiers. Both Naive Bayes model and decision tree are easy to use.

They are both used primarily for classification tasks, predicting the class or category to which a data point belongs.

Naive Bayes models calculate the probability to each class while decision tree shows a tree structure with conditions and leaf nodes.

They both show that a Youtube channel’s highest estimated monthly earning, video views monthly growth rate, earning rate and video views in total show a positive correlation with the yearly income, while decision tree clearly shows the conditions of nodes, so we can tell the decision path easily, but Naive Bayes models don’t show decision path. However, because of decision tree’s algorithm, it only shows the result of most significant features, so some other less significant features’ results may not be shown.

Evaluation

In this section, we are going to evaluate each model based on their precision, recall, F1 score and accuracy.

# Define a function to evaluate models
performanceMeasures <- function(model_name, pred, truth) {
  ctable <- table(truth = truth, pred = pred)
  accuracy <- sum(diag(ctable)) / sum(ctable)
  precision <- ifelse(sum(ctable[, 2]) == 0, 0, ctable[2, 2] / sum(ctable[, 2]))
  recall <- ifelse(sum(ctable[2, ]) == 0, 0, ctable[2, 2] / sum(ctable[2, ]))
  f1 <- ifelse((precision + recall) == 0, 0, 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall))
  
  return(data.frame(Model = model_name, Precision = precision, Recall = recall, F1 = f1, Accuracy = accuracy))
}

# Output the results(cite5:chatgpt3.5)
results_df <- data.frame(Model = character(0), Precision = numeric(0), Recall = numeric(0), F1 = numeric(0), Accuracy = numeric(0)) 

results_df <- rbind(results_df, performanceMeasures("nb_single1, training", train$nbpred, train$hyel_binary))
results_df <- rbind(results_df, performanceMeasures("nb_single1, testing", test$nbpred, test$hyel_binary))
results_df <- rbind(results_df, performanceMeasures("nb_single2, training", train$nbpred4, train$hyel_binary))
results_df <- rbind(results_df, performanceMeasures("nb_single2, test", test$nbpred4, test$hyel_binary))
results_df <- rbind(results_df, performanceMeasures("decision_tree1, training", train$tree_pred1, train$hyel_binary))

Part 2 - Clustering

Select the variables ‘subscribers’, ‘video.views’, “earnings_views”, “videoviews_monthlygrowthrate”, “subscribers_for_last_30_days”, ‘highest_monthly_earnings_fix1’, “Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment….”, “Population” for cluster analysis .

This part uses k-means clustering and hierarchical clustering methods respectively. The NbClust package provides numerous indices to determine the optimal number of classes in a cluster analysis. The data of the best class for k-means clustering is 2.The data of the best class for hierarchical clustering is 2.

By comparing the results of k-means clustering and hierarchical clustering, relatively speaking, the number of two different classes included in k-means clustering is relatively evenly distributed, and the division is more detailed. Hierarchical clustering is divided into two classes, but one of the classes has only one value, and the results of hierarchical clustering are not as reasonable as k-means clustering.

k-means

videoviews_monthlygrowthrate + earnings_views + video.views + subscribers_for_last_30_days + subscribers + Gross.tertiary.education.enrollment…. + Population

# Calculate distance matrix 
d <- dist(data_scaled) 
# Hierarchical clustering
fit.average <- hclust(d, method="average") 
# Get final clustering scheme with 2 clusters
clusters <- cutree(fit.average, k=2)
table(clusters)

Conclusion

In conclusion, we used Fisher’s score and information gain as feature selection techniques, and used Decision tree and Naive Bayes model to predict. We find out that both models show this result: a Youtube channel’s video views in the last year, video views monthly growth rate, highest estimated monthly earnings, subscribers, earning rate and the number of subscribers increase in the last 30 days show a positive correlation with highest estimated yearly earning, while Population, GDP per capita and gross tertiary education enrollment don’t show a significant correlation with the highest estimated yearly income.

As for feature selection methods comparison, we find out that in this project, Information gain can find more significant features. As for classifier comparison, after evaluation of performance, we find out all the decision tree model achieve perfect score while Naive Bayes models’ performance is poor. So we can draw a conclusion that in this project, decision tree model performs better.

In the clustering part, we used elbow method to decide the best number of clusters is 2, and find out that video views shows a positive correlation with yearly income. K-means shows a better clustering result than hierarchical clustering.
